1) This class is a bridge from byte streams to character streams: it reads bytes
and decodes them into characters using a specified charset.
2) For top efficiency consider wrapping an Inputstreamreader within a
bufferedreader.
3) readLine() - returns a line of text
4) println(string x) - prints a string and then terminates the line
5) serversocket(int port) - creates a server socket, bound to the specified port
6) accept() - listens for a connection to be made to this socket and accepts it
7) Most appropriate constructor - Socket(InetAddress address, int port)
8) getInputStream - returns an input stream for this socket
9) getOutputStream - returns an output stream for this socket
10) Date() - allocates a date object and initialises it so that it represents
the time at which it was allocated, measured to the nearest millisecond
11)
import java.util.Calender;

Calender calendar = Calender.getInstance();
SimpleDataFormat formatter = new SimpleDateFormat("dd-MM-yyy HH:mm:ss");
System.out.println(formatter.format(calendar.getTime());

